spec: asyncio_extra151
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(asyncio)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/asyncio.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/asyncio.html — Python asyncio module documentation"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source: Lib/asyncio/__init__.py"
  notes:
    - "This spec covers: asyncio.__dict__.__len__()==136 and asyncio.__dict__.__class__.__name__=='dict'; also asyncio.tasks.__dict__.__len__()==81 (largest submodule), asyncio.futures.__dict__.__len__()==40, asyncio.locks.__dict__.__len__()==21, asyncio.queues.__dict__.__len__()==20; submodule __name__ lengths: asyncio.__name__ len=7 ('asyncio'), tasks len=13 ('asyncio.tasks'), futures len=15 ('asyncio.futures'), locks len=13 ('asyncio.locks'), queues len=14 ('asyncio.queues'). All verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11."
    - "asyncio.__dict__.__len__()==136 — the asyncio package exports 136 names in its module __dict__ (a plain dict, not a mappingproxy, because asyncio is a module not a class). asyncio.__dict__.__class__.__name__=='dict' (len=4). Verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11."
    - "asyncio.tasks.__dict__.__len__()==81 is the largest of the four submodules: tasks(81) > futures(40) > locks(21) > queues(20). asyncio.tasks is the richest submodule, containing coroutine scheduling primitives (gather, wait, sleep, shield, create_task, ensure_future, as_completed, etc.) and the Task class. Verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11."
    - "All expected values verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11."
  created_at: "2026-04-11T00:00:00Z"

error_model: python_exceptions

